PLOTS OBSERVATIONS
==================
Notes for each plot in 02_data_visualization.ipynb.
Each entry: what the plot shows, what it means, and any modeling implication.


1. df['fare'].hist()  --  Distribution of fare
-----------------------------------------------
- Distribution is right-skewed: most fares cluster between $150-$300,
  with a long tail extending toward $600+.
- Run df['fare'].skew() to confirm. If skew > 1, apply a log transform
  before modeling (np.log1p(fare)).
- A few extreme high-fare routes will dominate RMSE if untransformed —
  the model will optimize for the rare expensive routes at the cost of
  the typical ones.


2. nsmiles vs fare  --  Distance vs average fare
------------------------------------------------
- Clear positive trend: longer routes cost more, as expected.
- Relationship is NOT perfectly linear — fare grows fast over short
  distances, then plateaus around $300-$400 for cross-country routes.
  This is a logarithmic-shaped relationship (cost per mile decreases
  with distance).
- Significant vertical spread at every distance: many other factors
  (carrier, competition, season, demand) affect price beyond distance
  alone. Distance alone won't be enough to predict fare accurately.


3. large_ms vs fare  --  Dominant carrier market share vs fare
--------------------------------------------------------------
- COUNTERINTUITIVE: routes where one carrier has 100% market share
  (large_ms = 1) have LOWER fares, not higher.
- This contradicts the monopoly intuition. The likely cause is
  CONFOUNDING with distance — see plot 4 below.
- Important lesson: high correlation alone is not enough to claim
  causation. Always check for hidden third variables.


4. nsmiles vs large_ms  --  Distance vs market share concentration
------------------------------------------------------------------
- Confirms the confounding: short routes (under ~500 miles) have
  large_ms close to 1 (single dominant carrier), while longer routes
  show much more spread (multiple carriers competing).
- The story: short routes are thin markets where only one airline
  bothers to fly. They charge less because demand is small and
  passengers are price-sensitive (driving is an alternative). It's
  not the monopoly causing low prices — it's the route's economics.
- Modeling implication: large_ms by itself is NOT a clean signal.
  Distance must also be in the model to disentangle the two effects.


5. avg nsmiles by quarter  --  Bar chart of mean route distance per Q
---------------------------------------------------------------------
- Nearly identical across quarters (~1000 miles avg), as expected:
  route distances are physical constants and don't change seasonally.
- This plot is not very informative — likely worth replacing with
  AVERAGE FARE by quarter, which would actually reveal seasonal
  pricing patterns (Q2/Q3 typically peak for leisure travel).
- TODO: redo as df.groupby('quarter')['fare'].mean().plot(kind='bar')


6. nsmiles vs fare_lg  --  Distance vs dominant carrier's average fare
----------------------------------------------------------------------
- Bimodal pattern at shorter distances (< ~1500 miles): a "main
  cluster" around $200-$300 and a clearly separate "low cluster"
  around $75-$150.
- Hypothesis: low-cost carriers (LCCs) — Spirit (NK), Frontier (F9),
  Allegiant (G4) — operate primarily on short-to-medium routes and
  charge 30-50% less than legacy carriers. Their entire business
  model produces this separate price regime.
- LCCs are clearly concentrated at smaller distances: the low
  cluster fades out past ~1500 miles and is essentially absent on
  long-haul routes. This matches LCC economics — their model relies
  on high-frequency short hops with fast aircraft turnaround. Long
  routes require more crew, more fuel reserves, and lock up planes
  for full days, which kills the cost advantage. Effectively, LCCs
  do not exist on transcontinental routes in this dataset.
- Verify with:
      low = df[(df['fare_lg'] < 150) & (df['nsmiles'] < 1500)]
      print(low['carrier_lg'].value_counts())
  If NK / F9 / G4 dominate the output, hypothesis confirmed.
- Modeling implication: the distance-fare relationship isn't one
  curve, it's two curves depending on carrier type. An is_lcc binary
  feature would help linear models. Tree-based models (random forest,
  gradient boosting) would discover this automatically by splitting
  on carrier first.
- This same pattern transfers to phase 2 international data:
  Ryanair, EasyJet, AirAsia behave the exact same way.
- Note: fare_lg itself is leakage (derived from the target) and must
  be dropped before modeling. The INSIGHT, however, is real and
  useful — it tells us is_lcc is a feature worth engineering.


CROSS-CUTTING TAKEAWAYS
=======================
- Distance is the single strongest predictor of fare, but with a
  non-linear shape and large residual variance.
- Carrier type (LCC vs legacy) is a hidden second axis that splits
  fares into distinct regimes.
- Naive interpretations of single-variable plots can be misleading
  (the large_ms case). Always check for confounding variables.
- The fare distribution is skewed and likely needs a log transform
  for linear models.

